          = \n|doublesrecord                  = \n|doublestitles                  =  \n|highestdoublesranking          = \n|currentdoublesranking          = \n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult    = QF (1961, 1963, 1964, 1967)\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult        = F (1966)\n|WimbledonDoublesresult         = QF (1969)\n|USOpenDoublesresult            = \n|OthertournamentsDoubles        = \n|MastersCupDoublesresult        = \n|WTAChampionshipsDoublesresult  = \n|OlympicsDoublesresult          = \n|Mixed                          = \n|mixedrecord                    = \n|mixedtitles                    = \n|AustralianOpenMixedresult      = 2R (1963, 1964, 1967)\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult          = \n|WimbledonMixedresult           = 4R (1967, 1968)\n|USOpenMixedresult              = \n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles   = \n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult      = \n}}\n\n'''Fay Toyne''' (born 18 December 1943), also known by her married name '''Fay Toyne Moore''', is a retired tennis player from Australia whose career spanned the 1960s.\n\nToyne was a doubles finalist at the [[1966 French Championships (tennis)|1966 French Championships]]. Partnering [[Jill Blackman]] they were defeated in three sets in the final by compatriots [[Margaret Court|Margaret Smith]] and [[Judy Tegart]].\n\nIn the singles event her best result at a [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] event was twice reaching the fourth round. At the [[1965 French Championships (tennis)|1965 French Championships]], she lost in the fourth round to [[Annette Van Zyl]], and in the fourth round of the [[1968 Wimbledon Championships]], she was defeated in straight sets by first-seeded and eventual champion [[Billie Jean King]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Wimbledon players archive \u2013 Fay Toyne (Moore)|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/scores/draws/archive/players/2eb919f5-eab6-4128-a672-049996e14475/index.html|publisher=AELTC}}</ref>\n\nIn 1964, Toyne won the grass court [[South of England Championships]] in Eastbourne, defeating Lorna Cornell Cawthorn in the final in three sets. In 1966, she won a single tournament in Prague, Czechoslovakia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article106934674 |title=Fay Toyne scores |newspaper=[[The Canberra Times]] |date=8 September 1966 |page=28 |via=[[National Library of Australia]]}}</ref>\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n\n===Doubles (1 runner-up)===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\" \n!style=\"width:40px\"|Result\n!style=\"width:35px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Championship \n!style=\"width:50px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:150px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:150px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:110px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#ebc2af;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss ||1966 || [[1966 French Championships (tennis)|French Championships]] || Clay || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Jill Blackman]] || {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Margaret Court|Margaret Smith]]<br> {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Judy Tegart]] || 6\u20134, 1\u20136, 1\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{WTA}}\n* {{ITF}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2016}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Toyne, Fay}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian female tennis players]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Wolbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGrand Slam finals:Formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fay_Toyne"}
